<subSubSection lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,303,1599,1625]" box="[189,303,1599,1625]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1599,1625]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1599,1625]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,1399,1645,1883]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Although cosmopolitan distribution is unlikely to occur in sponge species with a depth range limited largely to continental and upper bathyal waters, it is still possible that the present species from an oceanic island could have been capable of covering large distances. Thus, the reported occurrence of 
<emphasis box="[189,210,1753,1778]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van Soest" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Ridley &amp; Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[225,405,1751,1778]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="flagellifera" subGenus="Flagellia">
(
<emphasis box="[234,252,1753,1778]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">F</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[277,405,1751,1777]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">flagellifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from circumglobal southern ocean localities could be consistent with the occurrence of a single species. Here the literature data from the non-tropical southern ocean records of the species is reviewed. Despite numerous reports (see Remarks below), we consider that the only reliable record of 
<emphasis box="[221,242,1858,1883]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ridley &amp; Dendy" authorityYear="1886" box="[257,422,1857,1883]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Gellius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="flagellifer" subGenus="Flagellia">
(
<emphasis box="[266,284,1858,1883]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">F</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[309,422,1857,1883]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">flagellifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
originates from the 
<typeStatus box="[661,712,1857,1883]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
locality at Marion Island (South African administration).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,1399,1922,2018]" lastBlockId="22.[189,1399,266,538]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<bibRefCitation author="Boury-Esnault &amp; Van Beveren" box="[189,624,1922,1948]" firstAuthor="Boury-Esnault" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="1 - 175" refId="ref21417" refString="Boury-Esnault N. &amp; Van Beveren M. 1982. Les Demosponges du plateau continental de Kerguelen- Heard. Comite national francais des recherches antarctiques 52: 1 - 175." type="journal article" year="1982">Boury-Esnault &amp; Van Beveren (1982)</bibRefCitation>
reported 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ridley &amp; Dendy" authorityYear="1886" box="[732,935,1922,1948]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Gellius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="flagellifer">
<emphasis box="[732,935,1922,1948]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Gellius flagellifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Kerguelen Islands at a comparable depth of 
<specimenCount box="[295,378,1957,1983]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="generic">
<quantity box="[295,374,1957,1983]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="m" value="195.0">195 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
The shape of their specimens was also massive encrustations, up to 4.3 × 3 × 
<quantity box="[1310,1394,1957,1983]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="cm" value="0.8">0.8 cm</quantity>
. The oxeas were reported as 474– 
<emphasis box="[585,629,1992,2018]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">540</emphasis>
–589 × 13– 
<emphasis box="[766,795,1992,2018]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">14</emphasis>
–24 μm, clearly longer than those of the 
<typeStatus box="[1286,1340,1992,2018]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
. The flagellosigmas had their longest axis 88– 
<emphasis box="[664,693,266,292]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">98</emphasis>
–129 μm (= length of long ending) and their shorter axis 45– 
<emphasis box="[189,218,301,327]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">56</emphasis>
–67 μm (= width), close in measurements to those of the 
<typeStatus box="[892,943,301,327]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">type</typeStatus>
specimen, but no small flagellosigmas were mentioned. The shape of the flagellosigma in their paper is more narrow-elliptical than in the 
<typeStatus box="[189,242,371,397]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">type</typeStatus>
, and the long ending has a faint upturned hook. Normal sigmas have a wider range, 40– 
<emphasis box="[1310,1339,371,397]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">83</emphasis>
–131 × 2–5 μm, and in the illustrations clearly appear to be divisible into two sigma size categories unlike the normal sigmas in the 
<typeStatus box="[492,546,442,468]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">type</typeStatus>
. Therefore it is uncertain whether the Kerguelen material is conspecific with the 
<typeStatus box="[293,346,477,503]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">type</typeStatus>
, and for now is considered to belong to an unnamed 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Van Soest" authorityYear="2017" box="[973,1226,477,503]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Porifera" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Flagellia">
<emphasis box="[973,1090,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Haliclona</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1108,1216,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Flagellia</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
spec. until the specimen can be examined.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3836239" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3836239" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3836239/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" startId="22.[189,232,1856,1882]" targetBox="[189,1399,607,1817]" targetPageId="22">
<paragraph blockId="22.[189,1399,1856,2022]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,283,1856,1882]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 11.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Ridley &amp; Dendy, 1886)" authorityName="Van Soest" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Ridley &amp; Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[294,994,1856,1882]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="flagellifera" status="subgen. et comb. nov." subGenus="Flagellia">
<emphasis box="[294,411,1856,1882]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Haliclona</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[431,539,1856,1882]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Flagellia</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[559,688,1856,1882]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">flagellifera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ridley &amp; Dendy" box="[707,986,1856,1882]" firstAuthor="Ridley" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="470 - 493" refId="ref24141" refString="Ridley S. O. &amp; Dendy A. 1886. Preliminary report on the Monaxonida collected by H. M. S. ' Challenger'. Annals and Magazine of Natural History (5) 18: 325 - 351, 470 - 493. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222938609459982" type="journal article" year="1886">Ridley &amp; Dendy, 1886</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1005,1273,1856,1882]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species">subgen. et comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, holotype, fragment of BMNH 1887.5.2.252, from Marion Island, South Indian Ocean, SEM images of the spicules. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[298,319,1926,1952]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">A</emphasis>
. Oxea. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[410,431,1926,1952]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">A</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[431,440,1945,1959]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">1</emphasis>
. Detail of one of the apices. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[777,832,1926,1952]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">B–C</emphasis>
. Large category of flagellosigmas (I). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1282,1303,1926,1952]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">C</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1304,1313,1945,1959]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">1</emphasis>
. Detail of long ending of large flagellosigma. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[655,676,1961,1987]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">C</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[676,685,1980,1994]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">2</emphasis>
. Detail of short ending of large flagellosigma. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1257,1312,1961,1987]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">D–E</emphasis>
. Small flagellosigmas (II). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[420,438,1996,2022]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">F</emphasis>
. Sigmas.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="23.[189,1399,266,587]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<bibRefCitation author="Burton" box="[189,361,266,292]" firstAuthor="Burton" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="5 - 22" refId="ref21572" refString="Burton M. 1938. Non-Calcareous sponges. Scientific Reports of the Australasian Antarctic Expedition 1911 - 1914 (C. Zoology and Botany) 9 (3): 5 - 22." type="journal article" year="1938">Burton (1938)</bibRefCitation>
reported the species (as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1867" box="[670,753,266,292]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Adocia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[670,753,266,292]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Adocia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) from Eastern Antarctic Wilkes Land, directly south of 
<collectingCountry box="[223,334,302,328]" name="Australia" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Australia</collectingCountry>
, at a depth of 
<specimenCount box="[515,586,302,328]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="generic">
<quantity box="[515,582,302,328]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="m" value="36.0">36 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
He provided no data, other than remarking that the flagellosigmas reached 120 μm in the longest axis, a similar length to those of the 
<typeStatus box="[988,1041,339,365]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
, but not sufficient to conclude that the Antarctic specimen is conspecific. 
<bibRefCitation author="Gocke &amp; Janussen" box="[711,1026,376,402]" firstAuthor="Gocke" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="28 - 101" refId="ref22623" refString="Gocke C. &amp; Janussen D. 2013. Demospongiae of ANT XXIV / 2 (SYSTCO I) Expedition, Antarctic Eastern Weddell Sea. Zootaxa. 3692 (1): 28 - 101. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3692.1.5" type="journal article" year="2013">Göcke &amp; Janussen (2013)</bibRefCitation>
reported this species from the Eastern Weddell Sea, 
<collectingCountry box="[440,565,413,439]" name="Antarctica" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Antarctica</collectingCountry>
, at a depth of 
<specimenCount box="[723,804,413,439]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="generic">
<quantity box="[723,799,413,439]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.02" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="m" value="602.0">602 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
Oxeas were 570– 
<emphasis box="[1011,1055,413,439]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">643</emphasis>
–715 × 22– 
<emphasis box="[1186,1215,413,439]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">26</emphasis>
–29 μm, clearly considerably longer and thicker than the 
<typeStatus box="[669,723,450,476]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
. Flagellosigmas measured 80– 
<emphasis box="[1083,1127,450,476]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">106</emphasis>
–140 μm in the longest axis, 60– 
<emphasis box="[296,340,487,513]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">109</emphasis>
–155 μm in the shorter axis, also larger than the 
<typeStatus box="[920,971,487,513]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
specimen. The normal sigmas were 17– 
<emphasis box="[233,262,524,550]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">24</emphasis>
–31 μm, smaller than in the 
<typeStatus box="[591,645,524,550]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
. Although generally similar to the 
<typeStatus box="[1050,1103,524,550]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
, the spicule size data and the lack of differentiated larger and smaller flagellosigmas indicates a likely specific difference.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[189,1399,628,691]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
It is not possible to judge whether specimens reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pansini &amp; Sara" box="[877,1141,628,654]" firstAuthor="Pansini" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="203 - 208" refId="ref23834" refString="Pansini M. &amp; Sara M. 1999. Taxonomical and biogeographical notes on the sponges of the Straits of Magellan. Scientia Marina 63 (Supl. 1): 203 - 208. https: // doi. org / 10.3989 / scimar. 1999.63 s 1203" type="journal article" year="1999">Pansini &amp; Sarà (1999)</bibRefCitation>
from Magellan Strait are similar to the 
<typeStatus box="[394,445,665,691]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
specimen, because no description was provided.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[189,1399,732,942]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<bibRefCitation author="Dendy" box="[189,354,732,758]" firstAuthor="Dendy" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="269 - 392" refId="ref22096" refString="Dendy A. 1924. Porifera. Part I. Non-Antarctic sponges. British Antarctic (&quot; Terra Nova &quot;) Expedition, 1910. Natural History Reports (Zoology) 6 (3): 269 - 392. Available from http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 195204  page / 7 / mode / 1 up [accessed 25 Jul. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1924">Dendy (1924)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Bergquist &amp; Warne" box="[415,732,732,758]" firstAuthor="Bergquist" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 77" refId="ref21374" refString="Bergquist P. R. &amp; Warne K. P. 1980. The marine fauna of New Zealand: Porifera, Demospongiae, part 3 (Haplosclerida and Nepheliospongida). New Zealand Oceanographic Institute Memoir 87: 1 - 77." type="journal article" year="1980">Bergquist &amp; Warne (1980)</bibRefCitation>
reported specimens from northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1154,1312,732,758]" name="New Zealand" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
waters (Three Kings Islands), at depths of 
<quantity box="[614,691,769,795]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="m" value="200.0">200 m</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[751,873,769,795]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="m" value="90.0" valueMax="120.0" valueMin="60.0">60–120 m</quantity>
, respectively. The specimens differed in the size of the oxeas, with Dendy’s specimen possessing oxeas of only 210 × 8 μm, while those of Bergquist &amp; Warne were close to those of the 
<typeStatus box="[605,656,842,868]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
in size, 460 × 15 μm. Both specimens had small flagellosigmas of 46 and 64 μm respectively, and a single size of normal sigmas (20 and 28 μm respectively). Neither specimen appears very close to the 
<typeStatus box="[604,655,916,942]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
morphologically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[189,1399,983,1083]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<bibRefCitation author="Uriz" box="[189,318,983,1009]" firstAuthor="Uriz" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="54 - 73" refId="ref24825" refString="Uriz M. J. 1987. Sponges from the South-West of Africa: description of species. In: Jones W. C. (ed.) European Contributions to the Taxonomy of Sponges: 54 - 73. Sherkin Island Marine Station, Sherkin Island, County Cork." type="book chapter" year="1987">Uriz (1987</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Uriz" box="[329,389,983,1009]" firstAuthor="Uriz" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="9 - 157" refId="ref24877" refString="Uriz M. J. 1988. Deep-water sponges from the continental shelf and slope off Namibia (Southwest Africa): Classses Hexactinellida and Demospongia. Monografias de Zoologia Marina 3: 9 - 157." type="journal article" year="1988">1988</bibRefCitation>
) described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ridley &amp; Dendy" authorityYear="1886" box="[522,726,983,1009]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Gellius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="flagellifer">
<emphasis box="[522,726,983,1009]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Gellius flagellifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[795,899,983,1009]" name="Namibia" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Namibia</collectingCountry>
, SE Atlantic (at depths of 
<quantity box="[1199,1335,983,1009]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3649999999999998" metricValueMax="2.9" metricValueMin="1.83" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="m" value="236.5" valueMax="290.0" valueMin="183.0">183–290 m</quantity>
). The oxeas were given as 420–570 × 16–30 μm, much larger than the 
<typeStatus box="[971,1025,1020,1046]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
. In addition, the flagellosigmas and normal sigmas were larger, suggesting that the Namibian material could be specifically different.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[189,1399,1124,1224]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Samaai &amp; Gibbons’ (2005) description of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ridley &amp; Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[675,1022,1124,1150]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="flagellifer" subGenus="Gellius">
<emphasis box="[675,792,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Haliclona</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[808,893,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Gellius</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[909,1022,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">flagellifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Atlantic coast of 
<collectingCountry name="South Africa" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(
<quantity box="[283,346,1161,1187]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="m" value="15.0">15 m</quantity>
) differs from Uriz’ material and from the 
<typeStatus box="[854,905,1161,1187]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[948,969,1163,1188]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van Soest" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Ridley &amp; Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[986,1168,1161,1188]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="flagellifera" subGenus="Flagellia">
(
<emphasis box="[995,1013,1163,1188]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">F</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1040,1168,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">flagellifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having two size classes of normal sigmas, 73–91 μm and 25 μm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[189,1399,1265,1402]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
These comparisons lead to the conclusion that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van Soest" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Ridley &amp; Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[755,1148,1265,1291]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="flagellifera" subGenus="Flagellia">
<emphasis box="[755,872,1265,1291]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Haliclona</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[892,1000,1265,1291]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Flagellia</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1020,1148,1265,1291]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">flagellifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is so far endemic to Marion Island of the Prince Edward Islands archipelago in the Southern Indian Ocean. Specimens reported as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van Soest" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Ridley &amp; Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[334,707,1339,1365]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="flagellifera" subGenus="Gellius">
<emphasis box="[334,451,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Haliclona</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[472,557,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Gellius</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[578,707,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">flagellifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other ocean basins are regarded as likely different species.
</paragraph>
